{{Single source|date=November 2018}}[[File:Packard Station Sedan at 2015 Macungie show 1of5.jpg|thumb|right|1949 Packard Station Sedan]]

The '''Packard Station Sedan''' was a pseudo [[station wagon]] model produced by the [[Packard|Packard Motor Car Company]] of [[Detroit, Michigan]] between 1948 and 1950, using the [[Packard Super Eight]] platform.  By offering the Station Sedan, Packard could market a vehicle with station wagon attributes, but without the full investment costs associated with a full-blown station wagon program development.
==History==
The Station Sedan used a combination of steel framing and body parts along with structural wood panels to create a "[[Woodie (car body style)|woody]]" station wagon-like car.  Unlike other woody wagons of the day, which used wooden passenger compartments mounted to chassis of a particular car, the Station Sedan used a steel subframe and steel passenger doors onto which hard wood panels were mounted. The only wooden door on the vehicle was the rear gate assembly.
[[File:Packard Station Sedan at 2015 Macungie show 4of5.jpg|thumb|1949 Packard Station Sedan cargo area]]
Neither a sedan, nor true station wagon, the Station Sedan enjoyed limited success and was discontinued when the 1951 Packard models were introduced.

