{{Infobox automobile | name = Packard Model 30 | image = | manufacturer = Packard Motor Car Company | aka = | production = | assembly = [[Packard Automotive Plant]], [[Detroit, MI]] | predecessor = [[Packard Model G]] | successor = [[Packard Twin Six]] | class = | body_style = | layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel drive]] | platform = | engine = 432 cubic inch [[T-head engine]] | transmission = | wheelbase = 123.5 inches | length = | width = | height = | weight = | related = | designer = | sp = }}
The '''[[Packard]] Model 30''' was a luxury car introduced for the 1907 model year. It replaced the Model S. It featured a touring body with [[right hand drive]] and a crank starter mounted to a four-cylinder [[T-head engine]]. The pricey 30 was marketed just above the Model 18 (literally a 9/10 scale model of the '''Model 30'''). In 1911 Packard introduced the [[Packard Six]] as a 1912 model and phased out the four-cylinder '''Model 30'''s.<ref>Hemmings Classic Car Volume 6, Issue 5 February 2010 page 22-25</ref> The Model 30 was replaced by the [[Packard Twin Six]] as the top level car in May 1915.<ref>[http://ateupwithmotor.com/model-histories/packard-twelve-twin-six-history/] History of Packard Twin Six</ref>
