The '''Packard Pacific''' is an automobile manufactured by the [[Packard|Packard Motor Car Company]] of [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]] for the 1954 model year.<ref>{{cite book|last=Langworth|first=Richard M.| title=Illustrated Packard Buyer's Guide: All Packard Cars and Commercial Vehicles, 1899 to 1958| publisher=Motorbooks International|year=1991|isbn=0-87938-427-1}}</ref> It replaced the [[Packard Mayfair|Mayfair]] and was sold exclusively as a two-door [[hardtop]].
In the early 1950s, Packard used a numeric naming scheme that designated Packard's least expensive models as the [[Packard 200]] and 200 Deluxe, while two-door hardtops and [[Convertible (car)|convertible]]s were designated Packard 250 and its mid-range sedan the [[Packard 300]]. For model years 1951 through 1953, the 250 hardtop was named the Mayfair; for model year 1954 only, the hardtop was given the model name '''Pacific'''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Consumer Guide|first=Auto Editors of|title=50 Years of American Automobiles|year=1989|publisher=Beekman House|isbn=0-517-68640-6}}</ref>
The Mayfair, Packard's first hardtop offering, was created for the 1951 model year in order to keep in competition with [[Cadillac]], [[Buick]], and [[Chrysler Imperial|Imperial]] from [[Chrysler]], whose hardtop sales were booming. The Mayfair was named after the exclusive [[Mayfair]] district of [[London]]. In renaming it as the Pacific, Packard associated the model with its [[personal luxury car]] offering, the [[Packard Caribbean|Caribbean]]. Both the Mayfair and Pacific shared the same [[straight-eight engine]]s (a 327-cubic inch for the Mayfair and a 359-cubic inch for the Pacific)<ref>Consumer Guide, pp. 637-638</ref> with top-of-the-line, or "senior" Packards, but were mounted on the {{convert|122|in|mm|sing=on}} wheelbase of less expensive, or "junior" models. The Pacific came standard-equipped with Packard's [[Ultramatic]] automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite book|title=1954 Salesmen Facts Book – Packard and Packard Clipper|date=1954|publisher=Packard Motor Car Company|page=137|url=http://packardinfo.com/xoops/html/downloads/SalesFactBook54.pdf|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref>
The Pacific and Mayfair were distinguished by high levels of interior trim: for instance, leather upholstery was provided, and the cars' interior headliners were ornamented with chrome strips intended to suggest a convertible top. The cars were also given innovative exterior color schemes; most were given two-tone paint jobs (for example: "Carnation" (white) and "Amethyst" (lavender)), which were considered fashionable at the time.<ref>Langworth, p. 110</ref>
1,189 Pacific hardtops were built before production concluded for the 1954 model year.<ref name="classic" /> Starting in 1955, Packard renamed its senior hardtop the [[Packard Four Hundred|Four Hundred]].
